---
const imageBase = "/images/ai-search-guide";
---

<div class="ai-guide" data-ai-search-guide>
  <section class="guide-section" id="section-1">
    <div class="section-kicker">01 · The outcome</div>
    <h2>What it means to appear in AI search</h2>
    <p>
      Showing up in AI search does not mean winning one permanent ranking. It
      means an answer system can find, understand, and trust enough information
      about your business to cite it, mention it, recommend it, or send a
      qualified visitor to it.
    </p>
    <p>
      The result can change with the question, location, available sources, and
      platform. That is why the practical goal is not to “optimize for one
      chatbot.” It is to make the facts, expertise, and evidence around your
      business easier to retrieve and verify across the web.
    </p>

    <div
      class="flow-strip"
      aria-label="How a business becomes part of an AI answer"
    >
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>1</span><strong>A person asks</strong><small
          >A specific problem, comparison, or local question.</small
        >
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>2</span><strong>Sources are found</strong><small
          >Pages, profiles, reviews, documents, and trusted mentions.</small
        >
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>3</span><strong>An answer is formed</strong><small
          >The system synthesizes information it considers useful.</small
        >
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>4</span><strong>A next step happens</strong><small
          >A citation, branded search, visit, call, or inquiry.</small
        >
      </div>
    </div>

    <figure class="section-visual">
      <img
        src={`${imageBase}/section-1-search-flow.svg`}
        width="1536"
        height="1024"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        alt="A human-led visual showing a question moving through multiple business sources into one useful AI answer and a qualified website visit"
      />
      <figcaption>
        AI visibility is a source and evidence problem before it is a platform
        problem.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="guide-section" id="section-2">
    <div class="section-kicker">02 · The foundation</div>
    <h2>SEO, AEO, and GEO: what actually changes</h2>
    <p>
      Traditional SEO, answer engine optimization, and generative engine
      optimization are not three separate marketing systems. They are different
      ways of describing how discoverable content gets found, understood,
      selected, and presented.
    </p>
    <p>
      Google’s current guidance is direct: there are no additional technical
      requirements, special AI schema types, or new machine-readable files
      required to appear in its AI features. The same fundamentals still matter:
      crawlable pages, indexable content, clear internal links, useful text,
      good page experience, and structured data that matches what visitors can
      see.
    </p>

    <div
      class="table-wrap"
      role="region"
      aria-label="SEO, AEO, and GEO comparison"
      tabindex="0"
    >
      <table>
        <thead
          ><tr
            ><th>Discipline</th><th>Primary question</th><th
              >What good execution looks like</th
            ><th>Useful measurement</th></tr
          ></thead
        >
        <tbody>
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">SEO</th><td
              >Can search systems discover and rank this page?</td
            ><td
              >Strong intent match, crawlability, internal links, useful
              content, and authority.</td
            ><td
              >Impressions, clicks, rankings, qualified organic visits, and
              conversions.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">AEO</th><td
              >Can the page answer a specific question clearly?</td
            ><td
              >A direct answer supported by context, evidence, definitions, and
              a useful next step.</td
            ><td
              >Featured visibility, cited answers, referral visits, branded
              follow-up searches.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">GEO</th><td
              >Can generative systems understand and reuse the information
              confidently?</td
            ><td
              >Consistent entities, source-ready facts, original evidence, and
              corroboration beyond one page.</td
            ><td
              >Citation sampling, AI referrals, source mentions, assisted
              inquiries, and conversions.</td
            ></tr
          >
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="truth-note">
      <strong>The practical rule:</strong> keep SEO as the foundation. Improve the
      shape of the answers and the quality of the supporting evidence. Do not chase
      an acronym as if it were a separate channel.
    </div>

    <figure class="section-visual">
      <img
        src={`${imageBase}/section-2-seo-aeo-geo.svg`}
        width="1536"
        height="1024"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        alt="An editorial system diagram showing a strong SEO foundation branching into answer-ready content and citation-ready evidence"
      />
      <figcaption>
        AI-search optimization extends good search work. It does not replace it.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="guide-section audit-section" id="section-3">
    <div class="section-kicker">03 · Interactive audit</div>
    <h2>Check your AI-search readiness</h2>
    <p>
      Use this quick audit to find what to fix first. It runs entirely in your
      browser. Markethink does not collect or store the answers.
    </p>

    <div class="audit-shell">
      <fieldset class="audit-list">
        <legend>Which statements are true today?</legend>
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Fix crawlability and indexation before creating more content."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Search systems can access the site.</strong><small
              >Important pages are indexable, internally linked, and included in
              a current sitemap.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Clarify your core service pages before expanding into supporting articles."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Core service pages answer buying questions.</strong><small
              >Each page clearly explains the service, audience, process, fit,
              and next step.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Add direct answer blocks to the pages that already attract relevant questions."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Important questions receive direct answers.</strong><small
              >Answers appear early, then expand with context and evidence.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Standardize your business name, category, services, and locations across the web."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Business facts are consistent.</strong><small
              >Name, services, expertise, location, and contact details match
              across key profiles.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Publish first-party evidence instead of repeating general advice."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>The site contains original evidence.</strong><small
              >Process detail, examples, research, expert commentary, or
              approved proof supports the claims.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Strengthen trusted mentions, reviews, and profiles outside your own domain."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Other sources corroborate the business.</strong><small
              >Relevant profiles, reviews, publications, and expert mentions
              support the same entity.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Use only supported structured data that accurately matches visible page content."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Structured data matches visible content.</strong><small
              >Organization, LocalBusiness, Article, or other supported markup
              accurately describes the visible page.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
        <label
          ><input
            type="checkbox"
            data-audit-item
            data-recommendation="Create a simple baseline for organic visibility, AI citations, referrals, and conversions."
          />
          <span
            ><strong>Visibility and outcomes are measured.</strong><small
              >Search Console, Bing Webmaster Tools, analytics, CRM, and inquiry
              sources are connected.</small
            ></span
          ></label
        >
      </fieldset>

      <aside class="audit-result" aria-live="polite">
        <span class="score-label">Readiness score</span>
        <div class="score-row">
          <strong data-audit-score>0</strong><span>/ 8</span>
        </div>
        <progress data-audit-progress max="8" value="0">0 of 8</progress>
        <h3 data-audit-band>Build the foundation first</h3>
        <p data-audit-advice>
          Start by making the site crawlable, indexable, and clear about what
          the business does.
        </p>
        <button class="copy-score" type="button" data-copy-audit
          >Copy my first action</button
        >
        <small data-copy-status aria-live="polite"></small>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <figure class="section-visual">
      <img
        src={`${imageBase}/section-3-readiness-audit.svg`}
        width="1536"
        height="1024"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        alt="A marketing operator sorting eight business evidence tiles into one organized AI-search readiness system"
      />
      <figcaption>
        The lowest-scoring layer usually matters more than publishing another
        generic article.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="guide-section" id="section-4">
    <div class="section-kicker">04 · Content structure</div>
    <h2>Build pages that are easy to answer from</h2>
    <p>
      An answer-ready page does not reduce everything to a short paragraph. It
      gives the reader a direct answer, then earns trust with useful detail. The
      best structure depends on the question, but four layers work across many
      service and educational pages.
    </p>

    <div class="answer-demo" data-answer-demo>
      <div class="answer-demo-head">
        <div>
          <span class="eyebrow">Example question</span>
          <h3>How can a small business show up in AI search?</h3>
        </div>
        <div
          class="answer-toggle"
          role="group"
          aria-label="Compare weak and useful answers"
        >
          <button type="button" data-answer-view="weak" aria-pressed="false"
            >Weak</button
          >
          <button type="button" data-answer-view="useful" aria-pressed="true"
            >Useful</button
          >
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="answer-panel is-hidden" data-answer-panel="weak">
        <span class="panel-tag">Too vague</span>
        <p>
          Businesses should create high-quality content, use AI-search best
          practices, and build authority online.
        </p>
        <small
          >This repeats advice without defining the work, evidence, or next
          step.</small
        >
      </div>
      <div class="answer-panel" data-answer-panel="useful">
        <span class="panel-tag good">Answer-ready</span>
        <p>
          A small business improves its chance of appearing in AI search by
          making its site crawlable, answering specific customer questions
          clearly, keeping business facts consistent, publishing verifiable
          evidence, earning trusted mentions, and measuring citations and
          referral visits.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Direct answer:</strong> state the conclusion in plain language.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Context:</strong> define when the answer applies and what changes
            it.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Evidence:</strong> support it with accurate facts, examples,
            sources, or expert detail.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Next step:</strong> help the reader act without forcing a sales
            pitch.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div
      class="table-wrap"
      role="region"
      aria-label="Question to page mapping"
      tabindex="0"
    >
      <table>
        <thead
          ><tr
            ><th>Customer question</th><th>Best page type</th><th
              >Evidence to include</th
            ></tr
          ></thead
        >
        <tbody>
          <tr
            ><td>What do you do?</td><td>Focused service page</td><td
              >Scope, audience, process, boundaries, and clear next step.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Which option fits me?</td><td>Comparison or selection guide</td
            ><td>Decision criteria, trade-offs, use cases, and exclusions.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>How does it work?</td><td>Process or methodology page</td><td
              >Ordered steps, owners, inputs, approvals, and expected outputs.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Can I trust this?</td><td>Proof or expertise page</td><td
              >Approved examples, credentials, sources, process detail, and
              transparent limitations.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Do you serve my area?</td><td>Useful local page</td><td
              >Real service-area detail, consistent business facts, and local
              relevance.</td
            ></tr
          >
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <figure class="section-visual">
      <img
        src={`${imageBase}/section-4-answer-ready.svg`}
        width="1536"
        height="1024"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        alt="A useful answer card being assembled from direct answer, context, evidence, and a clear next step"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Concise answers work best when deeper evidence sits directly behind
        them.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="guide-section" id="section-5">
    <div class="section-kicker">05 · Corroboration</div>
    <h2>Strengthen the evidence beyond your website</h2>
    <p>
      Your website is the source you control most directly, but it is not the
      only source an answer system can encounter. Profiles, reviews, expert
      references, industry publications, directories, and local records can help
      corroborate who the business is and what it is known for.
    </p>
    <p>
      Consistency matters more than occupying every platform. Start with the
      places customers and search systems already use in your category. Keep
      facts aligned. Earn mentions by contributing something useful, not by
      manufacturing low-quality citations.
    </p>

    <div class="evidence-grid">
      <article>
        <span>Control</span><h3>First-party facts</h3><p>
          Service pages, about information, locations, authors, policies,
          processes, and structured data.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Control</span><h3>Original evidence</h3><p>
          Approved examples, research, expert commentary, process detail, tools,
          and useful documentation.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Influence</span><h3>Customer signals</h3><p>
          Authentic reviews, relevant discussion, branded searches, and accurate
          responses.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Influence</span><h3>Trusted mentions</h3><p>
          Industry profiles, expert citations, local organizations,
          publications, podcasts, and partnerships.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div
      class="table-wrap"
      role="region"
      aria-label="Evidence coverage matrix"
      tabindex="0"
    >
      <table>
        <thead
          ><tr
            ><th>Signal</th><th>Where it lives</th><th>What good looks like</th
            ><th>How to verify</th></tr
          ></thead
        >
        <tbody>
          <tr
            ><td>Core business identity</td><td>Website and major profiles</td
            ><td
              >Consistent name, category, services, location, and contact
              details.</td
            ><td>Quarterly entity review.</td></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Expertise</td><td
              >Author pages, articles, profiles, interviews</td
            ><td>Named experts connected to useful, accurate contributions.</td
            ><td>Review author and source coverage.</td></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Customer experience</td><td>Relevant review platforms</td><td
              >Authentic, specific feedback and responsible responses.</td
            ><td>Monitor quality and recurring themes.</td></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Independent recognition</td><td
              >Trusted category or local sources</td
            ><td
              >Relevant mentions that add context instead of repeating a
              listing.</td
            ><td>Track source quality and accuracy.</td></tr
          >
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <figure class="section-visual">
      <img
        src={`${imageBase}/section-5-evidence-network.svg`}
        width="1536"
        height="1024"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        alt="A small business connected to its website, trusted profiles, customer reviews, experts, and independent publications"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Strong entity signals are consistent enough to verify and specific
        enough to be useful.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="guide-section" id="section-6">
    <div class="section-kicker">06 · Measurement</div>
    <h2>Measure citations, visits, and business outcomes</h2>
    <p>
      There is no universal AI-search ranking report. Measurement works best as
      a set of connected signals: whether your pages are discoverable, whether
      answer systems cite or mention them, whether people visit, and whether
      those visits contribute to inquiries or revenue conversations.
    </p>

    <div
      class="table-wrap"
      role="region"
      aria-label="AI-search measurement by platform"
      tabindex="0"
    >
      <table>
        <thead
          ><tr
            ><th>Surface</th><th>What you can control</th><th
              >What you can observe</th
            ><th>Important limit</th></tr
          ></thead
        >
        <tbody>
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">Google AI features</th><td
              >Standard crawl, index, content, preview, and snippet controls.</td
            ><td
              >Overall Web search performance in Search Console, plus
              landing-page conversions.</td
            ><td
              >AI-feature traffic is included in overall Web reporting, not
              broken out in a separate Search Console report.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">Bing and Copilot</th><td
              >Bing crawl access, sitemaps, indexation, and page quality.</td
            ><td
              >AI citations, cited pages, and grounding queries through Bing
              Webmaster Tools AI Performance.</td
            ><td
              >The report measures citation activity, not ranking, authority, or
              placement within an answer.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">ChatGPT search</th><td
              >Whether OAI-SearchBot may access content, plus the quality and
              clarity of the sources.</td
            ><td
              >Referral visits, landing pages, conversions, and sampled
              citations.</td
            ><td
              >Allowing the crawler does not guarantee selection or citation.</td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><th scope="row">Cross-platform sample</th><td
              >A stable set of real customer questions and accurate source
              pages.</td
            ><td
              >Mentions, citations, answer accuracy, source diversity, and
              changes over time.</td
            ><td
              >Prompt sampling is directional, not a universal rank tracker.</td
            ></tr
          >
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="measurement-panels">
      <details open>
        <summary>Weekly: watch discovery and technical health</summary><p>
          Review indexation, crawl issues, important page impressions, and
          sudden losses. Fix access and accuracy problems before changing
          content strategy.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Monthly: sample real customer questions</summary><p>
          Use a stable, documented set of high-value questions. Record whether
          the business is mentioned, which sources are cited, and whether the
          answer is accurate. Do not treat one prompt result as a market-wide
          ranking.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Quarterly: connect visibility to pipeline</summary><p>
          Review AI and organic referrals, assisted conversions, inquiry
          quality, CRM source notes, and the pages involved. Keep the measures
          that help decisions. Drop vanity reporting.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>

    <figure class="section-visual">
      <img
        src={`${imageBase}/section-6-measurement.svg`}
        width="1536"
        height="1024"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        alt="A marketing operator reviewing AI citations, referral paths, landing pages, and conversions in one measurement workspace"
      />
      <figcaption>
        A citation matters most when it supports accurate discovery and a useful
        next step.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="guide-section" id="section-7">
    <div class="section-kicker">07 · Execution plan</div>
    <h2>A practical 30-day AI-search plan</h2>
    <p>
      Start with one priority service or topic. The goal is not to rebuild the
      entire site in a month. It is to create one complete, measurable path from
      customer question to trusted answer to business action.
    </p>

    <div class="plan-toolbar">
      <p>
        <strong>Use the checkboxes as a working plan.</strong> Your selections remain
        in this browser session.
      </p>
      <button type="button" data-print-plan>Print or save the plan</button>
    </div>

    <div class="week-grid">
      <details open>
        <summary><span>Week 1</span>Fix access and define the entity</summary
        ><div>
          <label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Check indexation, sitemap, canonical tags,
            robots controls, and internal links.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Choose one priority service, audience, and
            search intent.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Standardize the business facts used on the
            site and major profiles.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Record a baseline for impressions, visits,
            inquiries, and current citations.</label
          >
        </div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary><span>Week 2</span>Build the answer path</summary><div>
          <label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Improve the core service page around real
            buying questions.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Publish one supporting guide that answers
            a specific problem in depth.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Add concise answer blocks, useful headings,
            and accurate internal links.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Add appropriate structured data that matches
            visible content.</label
          >
        </div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary><span>Week 3</span>Add evidence and corroboration</summary><div
        >
          <label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Add approved process detail, expert input,
            examples, or original evidence.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Correct inconsistent profiles and important
            local or category listings.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Identify two credible contribution or mention
            opportunities.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Review authentic customer feedback for recurring
            language and questions.</label
          >
        </div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary><span>Week 4</span>Measure and improve</summary><div>
          <label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Review Google Search Console and Bing Webmaster
            Tools performance.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Sample the same high-value questions across
            relevant answer surfaces.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Check citation accuracy, referral landing
            pages, and inquiry quality.</label
          ><label
            ><input type="checkbox" /> Choose the next update from the weakest verified
            signal.</label
          >
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="source-box">
      <h3>Official documentation used for this guide</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a
            href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/ai-features"
